<li id="cite_note-68"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-68">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation book">Breen, Michael (2012). <i>Kim Jong-Il, Revised and Updated: Kim Jong-Il: North Koreas Dear Leader, Revised and Updated Edition</i>. <a href="John_Wiley_&_Sons" title="John Wiley &amp; Sons">John Wiley &amp; Sons</a>. pp.&#160;95–96. <a href="International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="Special_BookSources/978-1-118-15377-2" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-118-15377-2">978-1-118-15377-2</a>. "It [North Korea] remains the most extreme, closed, and repressive of the five states that officially remain communist. Indeed, it is worse today than any of those countries were at their worse. The intriguing explanation to this is that North Korea <i>is not communist.</i>" […] "Their [the North Korean] ideology, their underlying belief system has not been discredited. The thought of Marx, Lenin, Mao and Stalin may now be something for the historians. But North Korean thought has survived the passing of communism because what they actually believe has little connection to it."</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-69"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-69">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation book">Lansford, Tom (2007). <i>Communism</i>. Marshall Cavendish. p.&#160;85. <a href="International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="Special_BookSources/978-0-7614-2628-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7614-2628-8">978-0-7614-2628-8</a>. "Many scholars assert that some communist states, such as North Korea, are simply dictatorships that use the title 'communist' as propaganda to justify actions and policies to the outside world and to their own people."</span></span></li>
